===Etymology===
1437, from {{etyl|frm}} {{term|funérailles||funeral rites}} {{p}}, from {{ML.}} {{term|funeralia||funeral rites}}, originally neut. pl. of {{LL.}} {{term|funeralis||having to do with a funeral}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|funeris}}, genitive of {{term|funus||funeral, death, corpse}}, origin unknown, perhaps ultimately from {{proto|Indo-European|dheu-|to die}}. Singular and plural used interchangeably in English until c. 1700. The adjective {{term|funereal}} is first attested 1725, by influence of {{etyl|frm}} {{term|funerail}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|funereus}}, from {{term|funus}}.

